---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title =
    "Building a Transactional, LSM-Backed Storage Engine from First Principles";
const description =
    "A hands-on, live course in storage engine architecture, transaction concurrency models, and LSM and B+Tree structural internals";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
    <div class="max-w-[850px] mx-auto font-sans">
        <!-- Breadcrumb & Back Link -->
        <div class="mb-8">
            <a
                href="/trainings"
                class="text-sm font-mono text-zinc-500 hover:text-zinc-900 transition-colors inline-flex items-center gap-1"
            >
                ← Back to Trainings
            </a>
        </div>

        <!-- Hero Header -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <span
                class="inline-block text-xs font-mono font-bold text-blue-600 bg-blue-50 border border-blue-100 px-3 py-1 rounded-full uppercase tracking-wider mb-4"
            >
                Live Weekend Course
            </span>
            <h1
                class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 leading-tight mb-6"
            >
                {title}
            </h1>

            <p
                class="text-lg md:text-xl text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed font-normal mb-8"
            >
                {description}
            </p>

            <div
                class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 bg-zinc-50 border border-zinc-200/60 rounded-2xl p-6"
            >
                <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 text-zinc-500 shrink-0"
                        fill="none"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        stroke="currentColor"
                        stroke-width="2"
                    >
                        <rect x="3" y="4" width="18" height="18" rx="2" ry="2"
                        ></rect>
                        <line x1="16" y1="2" x2="16" y2="6"></line>
                        <line x1="8" y1="2" x2="8" y2="6"></line>
                        <line x1="3" y1="10" x2="21" y2="10"></line>
                    </svg>
                    <div>
                        <p
                            class="text-xs text-zinc-400 uppercase font-mono tracking-wider font-semibold"
                        >
                            Duration
                        </p>
                        <p class="text-sm font-bold text-zinc-800">
                            August 1-2 & August 8-9, 2026 (Weekends)
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 text-zinc-500 shrink-0"
                        fill="none"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        stroke="currentColor"
                        stroke-width="2"
                    >
                        <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
                        <polyline points="12 6 12 12 16 14"></polyline>
                    </svg>
                    <div>
                        <p
                            class="text-xs text-zinc-400 uppercase font-mono tracking-wider font-semibold"
                        >
                            Timings
                        </p>
                        <p class="text-sm font-bold text-zinc-800">
                            10:00 AM to 1:30 PM IST
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-8 flex justify-start">
                <a
                    href="#enrollment-section"
                    class="px-6 py-3 border border-zinc-300 hover:border-zinc-900 text-zinc-800 font-sans font-bold text-center rounded-xl transition-all"
                >
                    Secure Your Seat →
                </a>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- The Pitch -->
        <section class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-zinc-800 mb-16">
            <h2
                class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 border-b border-zinc-100 pb-2 mb-6"
            >
                The Pitch
            </h2>
            <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-700 font-sans mb-6">
                Most backend developers write application logic on top of
                black-box databases. In this live weekend course, we pull back
                the curtain and write the actual systems software that powers
                modern storage giants like RocksDB, BadgerDB, and Pebble.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-700 font-sans mb-6">
                Key-value storage engines form the foundational storage layer of almost all modern databases. CockroachDB relies on <a href="https://github.com/cockroachdb/pebble" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors">Pebble</a>, Dgraph is built on <a href="https://github.com/dgraph-io/badger" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors">Badger</a>, and etcd is backed by <a href="https://github.com/etcd-io/bbolt" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors">BBolt</a>. By understanding how a concurrent, transactional key-value store operates under the hood, you master the storage backbone of the systems you use every day.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-zinc-700 font-sans mb-6">
                We will write an embedded, multi-versioned key-value storage
                engine from scratch, moving step-by-step through the classic
                components of an <a
                    href="/en/blog/wisckey_ssd_conscious_key_value_store/#lsm-tree"
                    class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                    >LSM-Tree</a
                > architecture:
            </p>

            <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
                <div class="border-l-4 border-blue-500 pl-4">
                    <p class="my-0 font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900">
                        The Memory Layer
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mt-1">
                        Coding a multi-versioned Skiplist Memtable that natively
                        supports timestamp-ordered key versions.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="border-l-4 border-amber-500 pl-4">
                    <p class="my-0 font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900">
                        The Durability Layer
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mt-1">
                        Implementing an append-only Write-Ahead Log (WAL) with
                        strict fsync batching and state recovery.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="border-l-4 border-purple-500 pl-4">
                    <p class="my-0 font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900">
                        The Disk Layer
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mt-1">
                        Designing block-aligned immutable SSTables, parsing
                        encoding offsets, and writing an in-RAM <a
                            href="/en/blog/bloom_filter/"
                            class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                            >Bloom Filter</a
                        > to eliminate unnecessary disk seeks.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="border-l-4 border-green-500 pl-4">
                    <p class="my-0 font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900">
                        The Transaction Layer
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mt-1">
                        Building <a
                            href="/en/blog/serializable_snapshot_isolation/"
                            class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                            >Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI)</a
                        > to detect concurrent read-write conflicts and prevent data
                        anomalies without global locks.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div
                class="bg-zinc-50 border border-zinc-200/60 rounded-2xl p-6 text-sm text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed font-sans italic"
            >
                <strong>What this course is NOT:</strong> We will not focus on database
                administration, cloud tuning, or SQL querying. This is a code-first
                engineering deep dive into the software architecture of storage engines.
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Why should you join? -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2
                class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 border-b border-zinc-100 pb-2 mb-6"
            >
                Why should you join?
            </h2>
            <div
                class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-6 font-sans text-base"
            >
                <div
                    class="p-5 border border-zinc-100 rounded-xl bg-zinc-50/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-2">
                        Systems over CRUD
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed font-sans">
                        Escape the loop of building basic APIs and writing SQL
                        queries. Level up by coding the systems software that
                        sits underneath the application layer.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div
                    class="p-5 border border-zinc-100 rounded-xl bg-zinc-50/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-2">
                        Purely Hands-on
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed font-sans">
                        Write the code yourself. Build every core component of
                        the engine from scratch to a complete, thread-safe
                        transactional store with tests.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div
                    class="p-5 border border-zinc-100 rounded-xl bg-zinc-50/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-2">
                        Design Interview Edge
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed font-sans">
                        Understand storage engine trade-offs at an operating
                        system, file system, and hardware level. Confidently
                        explain write amplification, compaction, and transaction
                        isolation levels in Staff/Principal interviews.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div
                    class="p-5 border border-zinc-100 rounded-xl bg-zinc-50/50"
                >
                    <h3 class="font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-2">
                        L&D Reimbursement Ready
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 leading-relaxed font-sans">
                        This course is priced to fit comfortably within the
                        standard corporate training/L&D budget of most tech
                        companies. You'll receive a detailed receipt for easy
                        reimbursement.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Production Code Studies Highlight -->
        <section
            class="mb-16 bg-blue-50/40 border border-blue-100/60 rounded-3xl p-6 md:p-8"
        >
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <div
                    class="p-3 bg-blue-500/10 text-blue-600 rounded-2xl shrink-0"
                >
                    <svg
                        class="w-6 h-6"
                        fill="none"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        stroke="currentColor"
                        stroke-width="2"
                    >
                        <path
                            stroke-linecap="round"
                            stroke-linejoin="round"
                            d="M10 20l4-16m4 4l4 4-4 4M6 16l-4-4 4-4"></path>
                    </svg>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-2">
                        From First-Principles to Production-Scale Optimizations
                    </h3>
                    <p
                        class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed font-sans mb-4"
                    >
                        Building a storage engine from first principles is the
                        ultimate way to master systems programming, but matching
                        the scale of industry giants requires seeing how these
                        designs are optimized for production workloads.
                    </p>
                    <p
                        class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed font-sans"
                    >
                        Throughout our live sessions, we will build a fully
                        transactional, concurrent storage engine from scratch,
                        and then bridge these designs to the actual production
                        Go repositories of <a
                            href="https://github.com/boltdb/bolt"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                            >boltdb/bolt</a
                        >, CockroachDB's <strong>pebble</strong>, and Dgraph's <strong
                            >badger</strong
                        >. You will analyze how engineers solve disk page
                        layouts, lock partitioning, block-aligned commit
                        pipelining, and background compaction strategies under
                        heavy write load.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Curriculum -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2
                class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 border-b border-zinc-100 pb-2 mb-8"
            >
                Curriculum
            </h2>

            <div class="space-y-12">
                <!-- Week 1 - Session 1 -->
                <div
                    class="border border-zinc-200/80 rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 bg-white hover:border-zinc-300 transition-all"
                >
                    <span
                        class="block text-xs font-mono font-bold text-blue-600 uppercase tracking-widest mb-2"
                        >Week 1 - Session 1</span
                    >
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-3">
                        Foundations & B+Tree Architecture
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        Learn how data moves from memory to disk and explore
                        B+Tree architecture limits. This session establishes the
                        theoretical foundation for storage engine internals and
                        write-optimized storage engines.
                    </p>
                    <ul
                        class="space-y-3.5 pl-5 list-disc text-base text-zinc-700 mb-6"
                    >
                        <li>
                            Introduction to storage engines and system goals
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Introduction to block storage devices and
                            random/sequential IO
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding file organization and standard kernel
                            IO caches
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding logical in-memory structures vs
                            physical block layouts
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding Binary Search Trees (BST) and memory
                            heights
                        </li>
                        <li>Analyzing BST limits for disk-based persistence</li>
                        <li>
                            Introduction to B+Tree node layouts and design
                            trade-offs
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Demystifying how database indexes work
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Production Code Study:</strong> Deconstructing
                            <a
                                href="https://github.com/boltdb/bolt"
                                target="_blank"
                                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >boltdb/bolt</a
                            > to see how a production-grade B+Tree engine structures
                            its physical on-disk pages.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <div
                        class="pt-5 border-t border-zinc-100 flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-between text-sm font-sans text-zinc-500"
                    >
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >System Design:</span
                            > B+Tree Node Layout
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Week 1 - Session 2 -->
                <div
                    class="border border-zinc-200/80 rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 bg-white hover:border-zinc-300 transition-all"
                >
                    <span
                        class="block text-xs font-mono font-bold text-blue-600 uppercase tracking-widest mb-2"
                        >Week 1 - Session 2</span
                    >
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-3">
                        LSM Introduction (Hands-on)
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        Get hands-on by building the core write path of an LSM
                        engine. We will code a thread-safe Memtable and
                        implement an append-only Write-Ahead Log (WAL) to
                        guarantee crash durability.
                    </p>
                    <ul
                        class="space-y-3.5 pl-5 list-disc text-base text-zinc-700 mb-6"
                    >
                        <li>
                            Introduction to <a
                                href="/en/blog/wisckey_ssd_conscious_key_value_store/#lsm-tree"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >LSM-Tree</a
                            > architecture and component interactions
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing a multi-versioned Memtable and its
                            iterator
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing an append-only Write-Ahead Log (WAL)
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing crash-resilient state recovery from WAL
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding WAL rotation and implementation
                            patterns
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Production Code Study:</strong> Auditing CockroachDB's
                            <a
                                href="https://github.com/cockroachdb/pebble"
                                target="_blank"
                                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >pebble</a
                            > or Dgraph's <a
                                href="https://github.com/dgraph-io/badger"
                                target="_blank"
                                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >badger</a
                            > repository to see how a production-grade engine structures
                            its concurrent Memtable and commit pipeline.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <div
                        class="pt-5 border-t border-zinc-100 flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-between text-sm font-sans text-zinc-500"
                    >
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >Prototypes and Demonstrations:</span
                            > 3 (SkipList Memtable, Memtable Iterator, Append-only
                            WAL with Recovery)
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >System Design:</span
                            > WAL + In-Memory Storage
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Week 2 - Session 3 -->
                <div
                    class="border border-zinc-200/80 rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 bg-white hover:border-zinc-300 transition-all"
                >
                    <span
                        class="block text-xs font-mono font-bold text-blue-600 uppercase tracking-widest mb-2"
                        >Week 2 - Session 3</span
                    >
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-3">
                        SSTables & Bloom Filters (Hands-on)
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        Move data from memory to disk by designing SSTables and
                        optimize reads using Bloom Filters. This session focuses
                        on minimizing read amplification and disk seeks.
                    </p>
                    <ul
                        class="space-y-3.5 pl-5 list-disc text-base text-zinc-700 mb-6"
                    >
                        <li>
                            Understanding block-aligned immutable SSTable
                            structure
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing key-value data encoding and endianness
                        </li>
                        <li>Implementing block-level binary search</li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing block-aligned SSTables and block
                            iterators
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding <a
                                href="/en/blog/bloom_filter/"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >Bloom Filter</a
                            > theory
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing a basic, naive <a
                                href="/en/blog/bloom_filter/"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >Bloom Filter</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing a production-grade in-RAM <a
                                href="/en/blog/bloom_filter/"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >Bloom Filter</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Integrating <a
                                href="/en/blog/bloom_filter/"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >Bloom Filters</a
                            > into the SSTable read path
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Production Code Study:</strong> Deconstructing
                            Dgraph's <a
                                href="https://github.com/dgraph-io/badger"
                                target="_blank"
                                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >badger</a
                            > engine code to look at real-world block-aligned table
                            builders and RAM-to-disk serialization.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <div
                        class="pt-5 border-t border-zinc-100 flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-between text-sm font-sans text-zinc-500"
                    >
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >Prototypes and Demonstrations:</span
                            > 3 (SSTable Encoder, SSTable Index Search, Optimized
                            Bloom Filter)
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >System Design:</span
                            > SSTable Design
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <!-- Week 2 - Session 4 -->
                <div
                    class="border border-zinc-200/80 rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 bg-white hover:border-zinc-300 transition-all"
                >
                    <span
                        class="block text-xs font-mono font-bold text-blue-600 uppercase tracking-widest mb-2"
                        >Week 2 - Session 4</span
                    >
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 mb-3">
                        Transactions & Compaction (Hands-on)
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-zinc-600 text-base leading-relaxed mb-6">
                        Implement transactions with Serializable Snapshot
                        Isolation (SSI) and build a Leveled Compaction engine to
                        keep the storage engine optimized. This session
                        completes the transactional LSM engine.
                    </p>
                    <ul
                        class="space-y-3.5 pl-5 list-disc text-base text-zinc-700 mb-6"
                    >
                        <li>Understanding transactions</li>
                        <li>Understanding ACID guarantees in storage design</li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing durability and recovery at the
                            transaction layer
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding SQL isolation levels and write
                            anomalies
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding <a
                                href="/en/blog/serializable_snapshot_isolation/"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >Serializable Snapshot Isolation (SSI)</a
                            >
                            theory
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing a singular update queue for safe
                            concurrency
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing <a
                                href="/en/blog/serializable_snapshot_isolation/"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >Serializable Snapshot Isolation</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing transactional iterators with
                            multi-version reads
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Introduction to Compaction and delete tombstone
                            management
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Understanding Leveled and Size-Tiered compaction
                            models
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            Implementing an automated Leveled Compaction
                            executor
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Production Code Study:</strong> Analyzing transaction
                            conflict detection and background compaction in Dgraph's
                            <a
                                href="https://github.com/dgraph-io/badger"
                                target="_blank"
                                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                                class="underline hover:text-blue-600 transition-colors"
                                >badger</a
                            >.
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <div
                        class="pt-5 border-t border-zinc-100 flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-between text-sm font-sans text-zinc-500"
                    >
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >Prototypes and Demonstrations:</span
                            > 4 (ACID Transaction Manager, SSI Conflict Detector,
                            Transactional Iterator, Compaction Executor)
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <span class="font-bold text-zinc-800"
                                >System Design:</span
                            > Transactional, LSM-Backed Storage Engine
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Program Prerequisites -->
        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2
                class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold text-zinc-900 border-b border-zinc-100 pb-2 mb-6"
            >
                Program Prerequisites
            </h2>
            <ul
                class="space-y-3.5 pl-5 list-disc text-base text-zinc-700 leading-relaxed font-sans"
            >
                <li>
                    <strong>Go 1.24</strong> (or newer) installed on your machine.
                </li>
                <li>
                    An <strong>IDE/Editor</strong> of your choice (e.g., GoLand, VS
                    Code) configured for Go.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Intermediate proficiency in Go (or any systems-friendly
                    programming language like Rust, Java, or C++). Familiarity
                    with pointers, goroutines, and basic IO interfaces is
                    helpful.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Clear understanding of fundamental data structures (arrays,
                    hash maps, binary trees, linked lists).
                </li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Enrollment Section (Razorpay Checkout Box) -->
        <section
            id="enrollment-section"
            class="mb-16 border-2 border-zinc-900 rounded-3xl p-6 md:p-8 bg-zinc-950 text-white shadow-xl relative overflow-hidden"
        >
            <div
                class="absolute -right-8 -top-8 w-32 h-32 bg-blue-500/10 rounded-full blur-2xl"
            >
            </div>

            <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-between items-start gap-4 mb-8">
                <div>
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold mt-1 text-white">
                        LSM Storage Engine Course
                    </h3>
                    <p class="text-sm text-zinc-400 mt-1">
